President Joe Biden has announced his intent to nominate Saule Omarova as the Comptroller of the Currency, making her the first woman and person of color to serve in this role. Omarova is currently the Beth and Marc Goldberg Professor of Law at Cornell University and is the Director of the Program on the Law and Regulation of Financial Institutions and Markets. Her expertise lies in the regulation of financial institutions and markets, banking law, and the political economy of finance. She has previously worked at the U.S. Department of the Treasury and has experience practicing law in the Financial Institutions Group of Davis, Polk, & Wardwell. Omarova holds a Ph.D. in Political Science from the University of Wisconsin at Madison and a J.D. from Northwestern University.

Additionally, Claudia Slacik has been nominated for the position of Member of the Securities Investor Protection Corporation. Slacik has over 30 years of experience in the financial services sector, specializing in financial restructurings, risk management, corporate finance, and trade finance. She has worked for JPMorgan, Citibank, and Bankers Trust, and from 2013-2016, she served as the Chief Banking Officer at the Export Import Bank of the United States. Slacik has also served on various boards of directors and has been a Fellow at Harvard's Advanced Leadership Institute. She holds degrees from Smith College and NYU.